#  Day 48 – Task S-2: Documenting Tailoring Decisions in the System Security Plan | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## From Decisions to Documentation

Day 47 worked through the tailoring analysis — scoping out non-applicable controls, identifying enhancements, and supplementing the High baseline with additional controls. Today's Task S-2 is about translating those decisions into the formal documentation that becomes part of the System Security Plan.

The distinction between Day 47 and Day 48 is the distinction between analysis and record. The tailoring analysis is thinking work — evaluating each control against the system context and making reasoned decisions. The tailoring documentation is accountability work — recording those decisions in a format precise enough for an assessor to evaluate, an auditor to review, and a future ISSO to understand and maintain.

NIST SP 800-37 Task S-2 specifically asks for the tailoring decisions to be documented in the SSP with sufficient detail to explain what was decided and why. "Control inherited from AWS" is not sufficient documentation. "PE-3 physical access control to server rooms is not applicable to MyClinic's implementation because OpenMRS is hosted on AWS EC2 instances in AWS-managed data centers. MyClinic has no physical access to or responsibility for the data center infrastructure. Physical access controls for the infrastructure layer are maintained by AWS and validated through SOC 2 Type II (available in AWS Artifact, current as of [date]). MyClinic retains responsibility for physical security of clinic workstations and the clinic facility, which is addressed under PE-3 as a system-specific hybrid control for the endpoint environment" — that is sufficient documentation.

Today I work through how to write that level of documentation for the most important tailoring decisions in the OpenMRS SSP.

---

## What I Worked On Today

Task S-2 documentation has a specific structure for each tailoring decision: the control identifier and title, the tailoring action taken (scoped out, enhanced, supplemented, compensated), the rationale for the decision, the implementation description where applicable, and the residual risk where applicable. I worked through producing that documentation for each category of tailoring decisions from Day 47.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clicked most clearly today is that tailoring documentation serves multiple audiences simultaneously — and the documentation needs to be written with all of them in mind.

The assessor reading the SSP needs enough detail to determine what to test. If the documentation says "session timeout is configured," the assessor needs to know: what value was configured, where it is configured, how it is enforced, and how to verify it. Vague documentation creates assessment uncertainty — the assessor either has to ask clarifying questions (slowing the assessment) or document a finding for insufficient detail (which is not the outcome anyone wants).

The Authorizing Official reading the SSP needs to understand the security rationale without needing deep technical expertise. The AO needs to be able to answer: does this tailoring decision make sense? Does the organization's rationale hold up? Are the residual risks being documented honestly?

The future ISSO who inherits the program needs the documentation to be specific enough to maintain. A session timeout documented as "15 minutes — configured in Tomcat settings" is maintainable. A session timeout documented as "implemented per policy" leaves the next ISSO hunting for where the policy value came from and whether it was ever actually configured.

Writing for all three audiences at once is harder than writing for one — but it is what makes SSP documentation actually useful rather than just present.

