## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While finalizing today's documentation work I came across the **2018 Allscripts ransomware attack** — which I covered on Day 26 — but want to revisit specifically through the session management and contingency planning tailoring lens.

Allscripts is an EHR vendor whose cloud services were disrupted by a ransomware attack that took systems offline for several days. Healthcare practices that depended on Allscripts for their EHR found themselves unable to access patient records. Many practices had no documented downtime procedures — the CP-2(1) enhancement I documented today — and clinical operations were severely disrupted.

One specific detail that is relevant to today's tailoring documentation: some practices reported that staff had left OpenMRS and other EHR sessions authenticated on workstations when the ransomware attack propagated. Authenticated, unattended sessions that were not protected by session timeout allowed the malware to interact with the EHR through the authenticated browser session.

The SC-10 tailoring decision — 15-minute session timeout, configured and tested — directly addresses this attack vector. The documentation specificity I required today — exact timeout value, configuration location, verification method — is what makes the difference between a control that is documented and a control that is implemented and verifiable. An assessor who tests the session timeout and finds it configured correctly has confirmed that the control is actually protecting against this scenario, not just that it is documented in the SSP.

