## What I Am Still Thinking About

One practical question that came up in documenting the AU-2 enhancement: how should OpenMRS audit logs handle the patient identifier field for privacy purposes?

The HIPAA audit control requires the ability to determine who accessed which patient records. That requires the audit log to contain a patient identifier. But if audit logs are accessible to IT staff who would not otherwise have clinical access to patient records, the audit log itself becomes a disclosure of PHI — revealing that a specific patient identifier exists in the system and was accessed.

The standard approach is to use the patient's internal system identifier (the medical record number or OpenMRS patient ID) rather than demographic information in the audit log. The internal identifier links back to the patient record for investigation purposes, but without the name or date of birth it is less directly sensitive than a fully identified record. IT staff who need to investigate an audit log event can look up the patient ID in the system under appropriate authorization.

This is a nuance in the AU-2 documentation that I want to add to the SSP — specifying that the patient identifier field in audit logs uses the internal system MRN rather than demographic data, and that audit log access is itself subject to access controls.

